<subSubSection id="C30427F0FFF49D31FF83FDB7FEE3FBF1" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA1747BFFF49D31FF83FDB7FC59FCF1" blockId="1.[113,1089,628,1549]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FF83FDB7FF47FD11" bold="true" box="[113,230,628,652]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Recognized by the large, parallel-sided body (
<quantity id="4CE6D99EFFF49D31FD25FDB7FC9EFD11" box="[727,831,628,652]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.25" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="7.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" unit="mm" value="8.25" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="7.5">7.5-9 mm</quantity>
in length), unique color pattern (dark, shiny body with the three pairs of characteristic, pale, semitransparent spots on the hemelytra, 
<figureCitation id="132568FEFFF49D31FEFDFD77FE01FD51" box="[271,416,692,716]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[152,191,1466,1485]" captionTargetBox="[152,1127,214,1442]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[152,1127,214,1445]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1-8. Loristes species, habitus. 1-3 – L. decoratus (Reuter, 1908). 1 – male from Primorskiy Kray, Russia; 2 – female from Korea; 3 – male from Korea. 4-8 – L. paveli sp. nov. 4, 6 – male from Honshu, Japan; 5 – female from Honshu, Japan; 7-8 – male from Shikoku, Japan." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341378" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341378/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Figs. 1-2, 4-5</figureCitation>
), shiny dorsum, small eyes, weak transverse basal carina on the vertex, short antenna, incrassate antennal segment II that is subequal in length to the basal pronotal width, short labium that does not exceed the apex of the mesocoxa, impunctate pronotum with dense, pale, semierect setae, thick collar that is about as broad as the diameter of antennal segment II, tumid scutellum, scutellum and hemelytron with uniformly distributed, wooly, reclining setae, and the male and female genitalic structures described below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA1747BFFF49D31FF62FCB7FC3AFB91" blockId="1.[113,1089,628,1549]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="132568FEFFF49D31FEB3FCB7FE17FC11" box="[321,438,884,908]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[151,190,1546,1565]" captionTargetBox="[203,1072,616,1517]" captionTargetId="figure-161@4.[189,1088,597,1546]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 9-16. Male genitalia of Loristes species. 9-12 – L. decoratus (Reuter, 1908). 13-16 – L. paveli sp. nov. 9, 13 – genital segment. 10, 14 – right paramere. 11, 15 – left paramere. 12, 16 – vesica.Abbreviations: ls – lobal sclerite, or lobe-sclerite; pt – phallotheca; sgp – secondary gonopore; spc – spiculum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341380" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341380/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Figs. 9-16</figureCitation>
). Male genital segment simple, lacking notable additional structures dorsal to paramere insertions. Parameres with basic shape typical of tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FC07FC57FB9CFC31" box="[1013,1085,916,940]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Mirini">Mirini</taxonomicName>
; left paramere long, semi-circularly curved; right paramere short and straight. Vesica with several spiculi and/or lobe-sclerites that are fundamentally homologous within congeners (
<figureCitation id="132568FEFFF49D31FF8BFC37FF5AFB91" box="[121,251,1012,1036]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[151,190,1546,1565]" captionTargetBox="[203,1072,616,1517]" captionTargetId="figure-161@4.[189,1088,597,1546]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 9-16. Male genitalia of Loristes species. 9-12 – L. decoratus (Reuter, 1908). 13-16 – L. paveli sp. nov. 9, 13 – genital segment. 10, 14 – right paramere. 11, 15 – left paramere. 12, 16 – vesica.Abbreviations: ls – lobal sclerite, or lobe-sclerite; pt – phallotheca; sgp – secondary gonopore; spc – spiculum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341380" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341380/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Figs. 12, 16</figureCitation>
); seminal duct slightly expanded apically; phallotheca smooth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA1747BFFF49D31FF62FBD7FEE3FBF1" blockId="1.[113,1089,628,1549]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">
Female genitalia (
<figureCitation id="132568FEFFF49D31FEA0FBD7FE73FBB1" box="[338,466,1044,1068]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1491,1510]" captionTargetBox="[204,1011,687,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-218@5.[173,1029,670,1479]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 17-24. Female genitalia of Loristes species. 17-19 – L. decoratus (Reuter, 1908). 20-24 – L. paveli sp. nov. 17, 20 – interramal lobe. 18, 21 – sclerotized ring. 19, 24 – sclerotized rings and adjacent structures. 22-23 – posterior wall of bursae. Abbreviations: dlp – dorsal labiate plate; ds – dorsal structure; irl – interramal lobe; sdp – seminal depository; sr – sclerotized ring; vlp – ventral labiate plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341382" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341382/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Figs. 17-24</figureCitation>
). Sclerotized ring narrow-rimmed, ovoid; dorsal structure membranous, more or less spinulate; interramal lobe wide, covered with minute spines, not heavily sclerotized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30427F0FFF49D31FF83FBB7FE9DFB71" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BA1747BFFF49D31FF83FBB7FE9DFB71" blockId="1.[113,1089,628,1549]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FF83FBB7FEA5FB11" bold="true" box="[113,260,1140,1164]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FEFEFBB5FEC3FB10" authorityName=": YASUNAGA" authorityYear="1991" box="[268,354,1142,1165]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Loristes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FEFEFBB5FEC3FB10" box="[268,354,1142,1165]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Loristes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
now comprises two species which inhabit the deciduous forests in the temperate and cold temperate zones of eastern Asia – northeastern 
<collectingCountry id="F30934EBFFF49D31FC89FB57FC1CFB31" box="[891,957,1172,1196]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">China</collectingCountry>
, continental Russian Far East, 
<collectingCountry id="F30934EBFFF49D31FEC0FB76FECEFB51" box="[306,367,1205,1228]" name="Japan" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Japan</collectingCountry>
and Korean Peninsula (
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F098AFFF49D31FD9DFB77FC29FB51" author="KERZHNER I. M. &amp; JOSIFOV M." box="[623,904,1204,1228]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" pagination="1 - 577" refId="ref3508" refString="KERZHNER I. M. &amp; JOSIFOV M. 1999: Miridae Hahn, 1833. Pp. 1 - 577. In: AUKEMA B. &amp; RIEGER Ch. (eds.): Catalogue of the Heteroptera of the Palaearctic Region. Vol. 3. Cimicomorpha II. The Netherlands Entomological Society, Amsterdam, xiv + 577 pp." type="book chapter" year="1999">KERZHNER &amp; JOSIFOV 1999</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F098AFFF49D31FC60FB76FB9CFB51" author="YASUNAGA T." box="[914,1085,1204,1228]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" pagination="2 - 331" refId="ref3749" refString="YASUNAGA T. 2001: Family Miridae, plant bugs. Pp. 112 - 276, figs. 2 - 331. In: YASUNAGA T., TAKAI M. &amp; KAWASAWA T. (eds.): A Field Guide to Japanese Bugs II. Zenkoku Noson Kyoiku Kyokai Publ. Co. Ltd., Tokyo, 350 pp (in Japanese)." type="book chapter" year="2001">YASUNAGA 2001</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F098AFFF49D31FF83FB16FE90FB71" author="ZHENG L. &amp; LU N. &amp; LIU G. &amp; XU B." box="[113,305,1236,1260]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" refId="ref3910" refString="ZHENG L., LU N., LIU G. &amp; XU B. 2004: Hemiptera, Miridae, Mirinae. Fauna Sinica, Insecta Vol. 33. Science Press, Beijing, xix + 797 pp., 8 pls. (in Chinese, with English keys and descriptions of new taxa)." type="book" year="2004">ZHENG et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30427F0FFF49D33FF83FB37FE26FEE9" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="398" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA1747BFFF49D31FF83FB37FC76F991" blockId="1.[113,1089,628,1549]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FF83FB37FF50FA91" bold="true" box="[113,241,1268,1292]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Discussion.</emphasis>
Currently, no sister group hypotheses are proposed for 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FCB4FB35FC3DFA90" authorityName=": YASUNAGA" authorityYear="1991" box="[838,924,1270,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Loristes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FCB4FB35FC3DFA90" box="[838,924,1270,1293]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Loristes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. At first glance this genus appears to be allied to the large Holarctic genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FD2EFAD5FC5AFAB1" authority="Reuter, 1896" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1896" box="[732,1019,1300,1325]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Adelphocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FD2EFAD5FCCBFAB0" box="[732,874,1302,1325]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Adelphocoris</emphasis>
Reuter, 1896
</taxonomicName>
. However, based on the structures of the antenna, scutellum and male genitalia, this similarity is considered superficial. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FE9FFA95FE62FAF0" authorityName=": YASUNAGA" authorityYear="1991" box="[365,451,1366,1389]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Loristes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FE9FFA95FE62FAF0" box="[365,451,1366,1389]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Loristes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably most similar in overall appearance to the east Asian 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FF45FAB5FE54FA11" authority="Distant, 1904" authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1904" box="[183,501,1396,1421]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Philostephanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FF45FAB5FEFAFA10" box="[183,347,1398,1421]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Philostephanus</emphasis>
Distant, 1904
</taxonomicName>
, but the former genus has no synapomorphy shared by all members of the latter. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FE8AFA55FDCCFA31" box="[376,621,1428,1453]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Philostephanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FE8AFA55FDBDFA30" box="[376,540,1430,1453]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Philostephanus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
have distinctive structures particularly in the female genitalia as documented by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F098AFFF49D31FE14FA76FC8BFA51" author="YASUNAGA T. &amp; SCHWARTZ M. D." box="[486,810,1460,1484]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" pagination="101 - 180" refId="ref3818" refString="YASUNAGA T. &amp; SCHWARTZ M. D. 2007: Revision of the mirine plant bug genus Philostephanus Distant and allies (Heteroptera: Miridae: Mirinae: Mirini). Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 150: 101 - 180." type="journal article" year="2007">YASUNAGA &amp; SCHWARTZ (2007)</bibRefCitation>
, not known from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FC16FA75FB9BFA50" authorityName=": YASUNAGA" authorityYear="1991" box="[996,1082,1462,1485]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Loristes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FC16FA75FB9BFA50" box="[996,1082,1462,1485]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Loristes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Based on the general shape of the male and female genitalic structures, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FC9DFA15FC64FA70" authorityName=": YASUNAGA" authorityYear="1991" box="[879,965,1494,1517]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Loristes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FC9DFA15FC64FA70" box="[879,965,1494,1517]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Loristes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is assumed to have some relationship with 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF49D31FE4DFA35FD46F991" authority="Yasunaga, 1997" authorityName="Yasunaga" authorityYear="1997" box="[447,743,1524,1549]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Polymerias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF49D31FE4DFA35FD99F990" box="[447,568,1526,1549]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="396">Polymerias</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F098AFFF49D31FDCDFA36FD46F991" author="YASUNAGA T." box="[575,743,1524,1549]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" pagination="116 - 121" refId="ref3710" refString="YASUNAGA T. 1997: A new mirine plant bug (Heteroptera: Miridae) found in Kyushu Island, Japan and the southern Primorskij Kraj, Russia. Entomologist (London) 116: 116 - 121." type="journal article" year="1997">Yasunaga, 1997</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F098AFFF49D31FCEDFA36FC6BF991" author="YASUNAGA T." box="[799,970,1524,1548]" pageId="1" pageNumber="396" pagination="116 - 121" refId="ref3710" refString="YASUNAGA T. 1997: A new mirine plant bug (Heteroptera: Miridae) found in Kyushu Island, Japan and the southern Primorskij Kraj, Russia. Entomologist (London) 116: 116 - 121." type="journal article" year="1997">YASUNAGA 1997</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF6124F3FFF79D32FF6AFA79FDC8F99E" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341378" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5341378" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341378/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="397" startId="2.[152,191,1466,1485]" targetBox="[152,1127,214,1442]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8BA1747BFFF79D32FF6AFA79FDC8F99E" blockId="2.[152,1128,1466,1539]" pageId="2" pageNumber="397">
Figs. 1-8. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF79D32FF03FA78FEDDFA50" box="[241,380,1466,1485]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Loristes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="397" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF79D32FF03FA78FE97FA50" box="[241,310,1467,1485]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="397">Loristes</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, habitus. 1-3 – 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF79D32FDF0FA78FD52FA50" authority="(Reuter, 1908)" baseAuthorityName="Reuter" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[514,755,1466,1485]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Adelphocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="397" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="decoratus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF79D32FDF0FA78FDCFFA50" box="[514,622,1467,1485]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="397">L. decoratus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF8F098AFFF79D32FD88FA79FD4CFA50" author="REUTER O. M." box="[634,749,1466,1485]" pageId="2" pageNumber="397" pagination="484 - 499" refId="ref3572" refString="REUTER O. M. 1908: Capsidae novae palaearcticae. Ezhegodnik Zoologicheskago Muzeya Imperatorskoi Akademii Nauk 12 (1907): 484 - 499." type="journal article" year="1908">Reuter, 1908</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 1 – male from Primorskiy Kray, Russia; 2 – female from Korea; 3 – male from Korea. 4-8 – 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF79D32FDBCFA15FD3BFA75" authority="Yasunaga &amp; Jica-Sv, 2008" authorityName="Yasunaga &amp; Jica-Sv" authorityYear="2008" box="[590,666,1494,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Loristes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="397" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paveli" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF79D32FDBCFA15FD3BFA75" box="[590,666,1494,1512]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="397">L. paveli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2591512FFF79D32FD52FA16FD45FA75" box="[672,740,1493,1512]" pageId="2" pageNumber="397" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
4, 6 – male from Honshu, Japan; 5 – female from Honshu, Japan; 7-8 – male from Shikoku, Japan.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BA1747BFFF69D33FF62FF1FFE26FEE9" blockId="3.[113,1090,220,372]" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
In a wider geographical scale, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF69D33FE3DFF1EFD84FF69" authorityName=": YASUNAGA" authorityYear="1991" box="[463,549,221,244]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Loristes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="398" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF69D33FE3DFF1EFD84FF69" box="[463,549,221,244]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">Loristes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more or less similar to some genera of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF69D33FC25FF1EFF53FE8E" authority="Fieber, 1858" authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1858" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Calocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="398" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96AA869FFF69D33FC25FF1EFBE1FF69" box="[983,1088,221,244]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">Calocoris</emphasis>
Fieber, 1858
</taxonomicName>
complex mostly known from the western Palaearctic Region. Higher classification of such superficially similar mirine plant bug genera is still in great need of investigation. Further world level supra-generic revision is required to correctly ascertain these complex groups in the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C1E0FF8FFF69D33FEC9FE9FFE22FEE9" box="[315,387,348,372]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="398" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Mirini">Mirini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
